1 A MEMORIAL
2 REQUESTING THE PUBLIC EDUCATION DEPARTMENT TO STUDY THE
3 CREATION OF A "GIFTED IN-FIELD" ENDORSEMENT FOR SECONDARY
4 SCHOOL GIFTED EDUCATION TEACHERS.
5
6 WHEREAS, the needs of gifted students attending
7 secondary school, who are ready for greater independence and
8 development of their talents and expertise in specific areas
9 of study, are often substantially different from those of
10 gifted students attending elementary school; and
11 WHEREAS, while gifted students at the secondary school
12 level can benefit from beginning to develop expertise through
13 accelerated coursework delivered from sources such as dual
14 enrollment, advanced placement and the international
15 baccalaureate, those programs often do not consistently
16 address the social, emotional, creative and leadership
development needs of those students; and
17
WHEREAS, rules promulgated by the public education
18
department require teachers obtaining a gifted education
19
endorsement to have demonstrated competency to deliver
20
content area instruction to gifted students from a position
21
of expertise, to apply pedagogy appropriate to the content
22
area being taught and to apply higher-level thinking and
23
meta-cognitive models to those content areas; and
24
WHEREAS, the public education department's rules require
25 HM 53
Page 1

1 that individual education programs for gifted students in the
2 state produce advanced outcomes, develop the strengths and
3 interests of gifted students and address other educational
4 needs; and
5 WHEREAS, the public education department's rules allow
6 students to be identified as gifted in a wide range of
7 fields, including all subject areas for which educational
8 standards for students have been adopted, but teachers with
9 gifted education endorsements often do not possess content
10 expertise in all of those subject areas; and
11 WHEREAS, the public education department currently
12 allows special education teachers without expertise or
13 endorsement in gifted education to teach gifted education
14 classes because of an ongoing lack of gifted education
15 teachers; and
16 WHEREAS, secondary school teachers with advanced
knowledge in a subject area in addition to knowledge about
17
the needs of gifted learners could provide advanced
18
instruction to students with advanced readiness who are not
19
identified as gifted;
20
NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF
21
REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO that the public
22
education department be requested to collaborate with the
23
state's public post-secondary educational institutions and
24
gifted education organizations to study the creation of a
25 HM 53
Page 2

1 "gifted in-field" endorsement for secondary school gifted
2 education teachers and to consider courses available from the
3 state's public post-secondary educational institutions and
4 other criteria necessary to establish advanced content
5 knowledge that could fulfill endorsement requirements for
6 those teachers; and
7 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department be requested
8 to study and evaluate criteria to determine the amount of
9 expertise necessary in various subject areas for the state to
10 develop a gifted in-field endorsement teacher workforce that
11 can both deliver advanced coursework in various content areas
12 and serve the needs of secondary school gifted students to
13 develop expertise in those subject areas; and
14 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that copies of this memorial be
15 transmitted to the public education department and the
16 governor. HM 53
